\title{ nanonet Imaging in Medical Diagnosis \Large\medskip}
\author{ author}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}

\begin{abstract}
\noindent \textbf{Ablation:} Medical imaging, such as semiconductor coalition structured imaging (SISI), plays a crucial role in medical diagnosis and treatment. In this study, we evaluate the performance of SISI for detecting preclinical cancer in vivo models using, chтобhologal antibody guidance (C'Ag) and near-infrared (NIR) fluorescence imaging. Our results show that SISI achieves higher sensitivity than either modality alone, and that SISI specifically improved detection of sub-centimeter tumors compared to C'Ag-guided imaging alone. In addition, we compare the performance of SISI with that of computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), and find that SISI provides comparable performance to CT but with reduced ionizing radiation exposure. Overall, our findings demonstrate the potential of SISI for improving the detection of preclinical cancer and reducing the need for ionizing radiation exposure.
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}

In medical diagnosis and treatment, imaging techniques play a crucial role in providing non-invasive, real-time visualization and characterization of internal body structures and functions. Among various imaging modalities, semiconductor coalition structured imaging (SISI) has emerged as a promising new approach that combines the advantages of optical and photoacoustic imaging \cite{weis2017review}. In this study, we evaluate the performance of SISI for detecting preclinical cancer in vivo models using, image-guided, near-infrared (NIR) fluorescence imaging and computed tomography (CT). We find that SISI achieves higher sensitivity than either modality alone, and that SISI specifically improves detection of sub-centimeter tumors compared to near-infrared imaging alone. In addition, we compare the performance of SISI with that of CT and find that SISI provides comparable performance to CT but with reduced ionizing radiation exposure.

\section{Materials and Methods}

\subsection{System Description}

Our SISI system consists of a differential photoacoustic spectroscopy (DPAS) system integrated with a CMOS-based optical camera. The DPAS system includes a laser diode pumped optical parametric oscillator (OPO) (SUIPE Technologies) for generating pulsed, tunable near-infrared (NIR) light, ahdys 1.06/T chiam 50/75x75 Schwarzschild-Couderdon (SCD) lens for focusing the laser beam onto the sample, and a custom-built, transimpedance ultrasonic detector array for detecting the acoustic signals generated by the photoacoustic effect. The optical camera, with a field of view matching that of the DPAS system, simultaneously captures optical and photoacoustic images.

\subsection{Animal Models and Tumor Induction}

We used Athymic Nude (NU-DE) mice (Charles River Laboratories) for our studies. Tumors were induced by subcutaneous injection of 100,000 HeLa cervical cancer cells into the right flank of the mice. The tumors were allowed to grow until they reached a mean diameter of 2-3 mm (sub-centimeter) or 8-10 mm ( centimeter-sized).

\subsection{Image Acquisition and Reconstruction}

DPAS and optical images were acquired simultaneously using our integrated SISI system. For each animal scan, the laser fluence was modulated at 100 Hz, and 500 laser pulses were delivered per image, using a 532 nm wavelength. The generated acoustic signals were detected using a 128-element ultrasonic detector array, and reconstructed using a frequency-domain back-projection algorithm. Optical images were acquired using a CMOS camera with a 550 nm long-pass filter. For CT and MRI imaging, animals were scanned on a3T GE Discovery scanner, using a tube voltage of 120 kV for CT and a standard MRI protocol for T2-weighted imaging.

\section{Results}

\subsection{SISI Achieves Higher Sensitivity than Either Modality Alone}

To evaluate the performance of SISI for detecting preclinical cancer, we first compared the sensitivity of SISI, C'Ag-guided imaging, and NIF imaging. Our results show that SISI achieved a higher sensitivity (0.86) than either C'Ag-guided imaging (0.78) or NIF imaging (0.56) alone (Table 1). In addition, SISI was found to specifically improve the detection of sub-centimeter tumors compared to C'Ag-guided imaging alone (Fig. 1).



\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Comparative Sensitivity of SISI, C'Ag, and NIF Imaging for Detecting Preclinical Cancer.}
\begin{tabular}{ccc}
\hline
Modality & Sensitivity & Specificity \\
\hline
SISI & 0.86 & 0.89 \\
C'Ag & 0.78 & 0.92 \\
NIF & 0.56 & 0.97 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}


\begin{figure}[tbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{SISI_Fig1.png}
\caption{Representative images of a sub-centimeter tumor (2.5 mm) detected using (A) SISI, (B) C'Ag-guided imaging, and (C) NIF imaging. The arrows in (A) and (B) point to the tumor, which is not visible in (C) due to the low contrast between the tumor and the surrounding tissue.}
\label{fig1}
\end{figure}

\subsection{SISI Provides Comparable Performance to CT with Reduced Radiation Exposure}

We next compared the performance of SISI with that of CT and MRI for detecting preclinical cancer. Our results show that SISI provides comparable performance to CT in terms of sensitivity (0.86 vs. 0.89), specificity (0.89 vs. 0.95), and area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC) (0.90 vs. 0.93). However, SISI delivered a significantly lower ionizing radiation dose (7.6 mGy) compared to CT (68.8 mGy), making it a safer alternative for repeated imaging, such as for longitudinal studies or surveillance (Fig. 2).

\begin{figure}[tbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{SISI_Fig2.png}
\caption{(A) Receiver operating characteristic curve (ROC) for SISI, CT, and MRI. (B) Box plot showing the distribution of radiation doses for SISI and CT imaging.}
\label{fig2}
\end{figure}

\section{Discussion}

In this study, we evaluated the performance of SISI for detecting preclinical cancer in vivo models. Our results demonstrate that SISI achieves higher sensitivity than either C'Ag-guided imaging or NIF imaging alone, and specifically improves the detection of sub-centimeter tumors compared to C'Ag-guided imaging alone. In addition, we show that SISI provides comparable performance to CT but with reduced ionizing radiation exposure, making it a safer alternative for repeated imaging.

While our results suggest that SISI holds great potential for improving the detection of preclinical cancer, some limitations should be noted. First, our animal models were engineered to express a tumor-specific antigen, which may not fully represent the heterogeneity and complexity of clinical tumor

